Finding Percent Change From 2008 to 2012 One of the the things I was most interested in this data was how much the turnout changed between 2008 and 2012. My hypothesis was that turnout dropped in 2012 because there wasnât quite the same enthusiasm there was in 2008. But I was wrong. The data shows that turnout increased dramatically. Now, I think that thereâs an error between the two and that the 2012 data is probably more detailed and better done, accounting for a good chunk of the increase. But itâs still an interesting part of the data to explore.

Reworking the data We suspected that one of the causes for the unreal information found in the previous graph is the original state of the graph. We found it on a government site on an excel sheet, and tried to just save that as a csv and use that data straight. This proved difficult, so we went into the data to try and modify it to get rid of some of the unnecessary information. Here are the heads of our reformed data tables

These graphs have several interesting, nonobvious components. First of all, it seems that on the whole, the Democrats either experienced a slight increase A sharp decline, or held steady in the polls. There were no states where they had very sharp increases. This is likely because Obama, as an incumbant, had lost a lot of his initial luster as a candidate. On the other hand, the republicans made some notisable increases in a few states, implying a return of those states to their natural political color. However, we canât confirm this without seeing at least a few more election results, and that is beyond the scope of this process. Overall, it seems like voter particpation is slightly down on this graph.

The second graph aslo has some interesting stories to tell. In very populace states such as California or Texas, Voter particpation is at its lowest. If we compare the two graphs, its appears that neither of those states had âcloseâ elections. We can thus say that Low voter particpation and Blowout elections are correlated, althought we canât say which causes which. I would guess that blow out elections cause lowe particpation, as people feel that their vote does not count, but I do not have hard evidence to support this. In the same way, Battleground states like Florida and Ohio have very high voter particatpion, further strengthening the idea of correlation. Again though, more years would allow us to draw better conclusions. Iâm very interested what the particpation of say Nixonâs re-election, where he won 48 states, was compared to the average election.
